name: fluctuation-in-the-diet-of-california-gulls-larus-californicus-at-alviso-ca
notes: The primary objective of this study is to examine chick diet at the California gull  colony in Alviso, California in an attempt to better understand how the gulls are  foraging in the south San Francisco Bay habitat. Specifically, fluctuations in chick diet with respect to time, tidal cycle, and chick age have been examined. California gulls are among the several species of Larus gulls having undergone an increase in population in the twentieth century (Hunt 1972). Since the 1930's both the number of California gulls breeding in the northwestern United States and the number of breeding colonies have increased (Conover 1983). The Alviso colony, discovered in 1980 represents a western and slightly southern extension of the California gulls' breeding range. As the first colony situated on a Pacific coast estuary, it also represents a departure from the species' typical nesting habitat of islands in freshwater or saline lakes in the interior of the western U.S. and Canada (Jones 1986). The Alviso colony has grown from around 12 nests in 1980 to *** nests in 1987 (Jones 1986, Peg Woodin pers. comm.). Jones (1986) reports that reproductive success at  the Alviso colony in 1983 and 1984 was comparable to that at other colonies and that chick weight at fledging may have been slightly higher. In the south San Francisco Bay the gulls have access to a variety of foraging habitats. Based on chick diet the gulls were foraging in fresh and salt water, on salt evaporation ponds, beaches, levees, meadows, agricultural fields, and at garbage dumps (Jones 1986). He attributes the success of the Alviso colony in part to an abundant food supply.
